<paragraph id="8BF6070DFF87F74EFF38FE9B2519FE91" blockId="28.[189,520,265,296]" box="[189,520,265,296]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<heading id="D0BEB061FF87F74EFF38FE9B2519FE91" bold="true" box="[189,520,265,296]" fontSize="13" level="1" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B93DDB1FFF87F74EFF38FE9B2519FE91" bold="true" box="[189,520,265,296]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B93DDB1FFF87F74EFF38FE9B27E4FE91" bold="true" box="[189,245,265,296]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">The</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C497C8EFF87F74EFF78FE9B26BBFE91" authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1858" box="[253,426,265,296]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Callipia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parrhasiata">parrhasiata</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B93DDB1FFF87F74EFE36FE982519FE91" bold="true" box="[435,520,266,296]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">group</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF6070DFF87F74EFF38FED3232FFDE2" blockId="28.[189,1399,321,604]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
This group comprises most species; I acknowledge here 12 taxa at species level with one of them comprising two geographically separated subspecies (
<taxonomicName id="4C497C8EFF87F74EFCD9FEF424EEFEC6" authority="Brehm, 2018" authorityName="Brehm" authorityYear="2018" box="[860,1023,357,384]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Callipia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wojtusiaki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B93DDB1FFF87F74EFCD9FEF424EEFEC6" box="[860,1023,357,384]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. wojtusiaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A20E6664FF87F74EFB8BFEF42365FE39" box="[1038,1140,358,384]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
). Most species have conspicuous rosy or pink wing bases, but in four species (distributed from central 
<collectingCountry id="F35E479DFF87F74EFB35FE1923F7FE1C" box="[1200,1254,395,421]" name="Peru" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Peru</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry id="F35E479DFF87F74EFF38FE3D2625FE73" box="[189,308,431,458]" name="Argentina" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Argentina</collectingCountry>
) the base colour is more intensive and ranges from orange to red. The rosy/ pink species are distributed from 
<collectingCountry id="F35E479DFF87F74EFE0CFE4126ECFE54" box="[393,509,467,493]" name="Colombia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Colombia</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="F35E479DFF87F74EFDAFFE412595FE54" box="[554,644,467,493]" name="Bolivia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. Unlike in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C497C8EFF87F74EFCBBFE4624B9FE54" authorityName="  Dognin. All" authorityYear="1913" box="[830,936,468,493]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Callipia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vicinaria">
<emphasis id="B93DDB1FFF87F74EFCBBFE4624B9FE54" box="[830,936,468,493]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">vicinaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, there is no pronounced sexual dimorphism, but females are considerably larger than males. Unfortunately, the male genitalia only offer very limited diagnostic characters and 
<collectionCode id="ED589FC8FF87F74EFD38FD8F25ECFD8E" box="[701,765,541,567]" country="Australia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">DNA</collectionCode>
barcoding in combination with distributional data will sometimes be the only reliable way of distinguishing closely related species.
</paragraph>
